### 17. Coin Request Approval Flow Fixes

**Problem:** The coin-requests approval flow had three bugs: (1) notification content was passed as a raw string instead of an object, causing encryption to fail; (2) status values were inconsistent (`approved` vs `APPROVED`, `pending` vs `PENDING`); (3) subsequent `REQUEST_COINS` messages returned `pending_approval` but were never stored in the DB — so the hub operator had nothing to approve.

**Fix:**
- Wrapped notification content in an object (`{"text": "..."}`) and disabled encryption for CLI notifications
- Standardized all status values to uppercase (`APPROVED`, `PENDING`)
- Added `request_id` to the pending response so users know what to approve
- Added `_record_pending_coin_request()` in `agent_stream.py` — subsequent requests are now stored as `PENDING` in the hermes SQLite DB with a generated `request_id`, enabling `aitbc coin-requests approve/execute` flow
- Fixed CLI env var loading: `node.env` now loaded with `override=True` so `BLOCKCHAIN_RPC_URL=localhost:8202` takes precedence over `blockchain.env`'s public URL when running on the hub

**Files changed:**
- `apps/agent-coordinator/src/app/websocket/agent_stream.py` — add `_record_pending_coin_request()`, uppercase status, include `request_id` in response
- `apps/hermes/src/hermes_service/handlers/request_coins_handler.py` — wrap content, uppercase status
- `cli/aitbc_cli/commands/coin_requests.py` — `node.env` override=True, wrap notification content, `encrypt=False`
- `cli/aitbc_cli/commands/hermes.py` — display `request_id` in pending output

### 18. Lease Heartbeat Frequency Fix

**Problem:** The subscription client's `_heartbeat_loop()` had an `else` branch that sent a heartbeat every 60 seconds even when the lease was healthy. Since `extend_lease()` resets the expiry to `now + 3600s` on every call, the lease got extended every minute — producing a log line on the hub every minute and unnecessary network traffic.

**Fix:** Removed the `else` branch. Heartbeats now only fire when the lease is within `lease_renewal_threshold` (300s) of expiry. With defaults (1h lease, 300s threshold), heartbeats fire roughly once every ~55 minutes instead of once per minute.

**Files changed:**
- `apps/blockchain-node/src/aitbc_chain/subscription_client.py` — remove unnecessary `else` heartbeat branch

### 19. Lease Tracker: Client IP Tracking

**Problem:** The lease tracker logged expiry timestamps as raw Unix timestamps and didn't track client IPs, making it hard to debug subscription issues from the journal.

**Fix:** Added human-readable expiry timestamps (`_fmt_expiry()`) to all lease log lines and `client_ip` tracking through `register_subscriber()`, `extend_lease()`, and `SubscriberInfo`.

**Files changed:**
- `apps/blockchain-node/src/aitbc_chain/lease_tracker.py` — add `_fmt_expiry()`, `client_ip` field in `SubscriberInfo`, `register_subscriber()`, `extend_lease()`
- `apps/blockchain-node/src/aitbc_chain/rpc/router.py` — inject `Request` object to extract `client_ip`, pass to subscription handlers
- `apps/blockchain-node/src/aitbc_chain/rpc/subscription.py` — pass `client_ip` through to lease tracker, include in `/rpc/subscribers` response

### 20. `update.sh` — Safe Update Script for Existing Nodes

**Problem:** After `git pull`, operators had to manually sync venvs, relink systemd units, restart services, and run health checks. The existing `weekly_maintenance.sh` was incomplete (only restarted 2 services, didn't handle systemd relinking or multiple venvs).

**Fix:** Created `scripts/deployment/update.sh` — the update counterpart to `setup.sh`. Idempotent and safe to run after every pull. Performs:
1. Pre-update backup (triggers `aitbc-backup.service`, waits for completion)
2. `git pull` from `https://github.com/oib/AITBC.git` (with stash safety for local changes)
3. Sync Python venv (reinstalls requirements + CLI via `install-profiles.sh`)
4. Relink systemd unit files (role-aware, via `link-systemd.sh`)
5. `systemctl daemon-reload` + ensure role-appropriate services are enabled
6. Restart all running aitbc services
7. Health check
8. Summary with DB migration reminder

Flags: `--no-pull`, `--no-restart`, `--skip-backup`, `--remote <url>`

**Files changed:**
- `scripts/deployment/update.sh` — new script (427 lines)
- `.gitignore` — allowlist `scripts/deployment/update.sh`
- `docs/getting-started/UPDATE.md` — new comprehensive guide (360 lines)
- `docs/getting-started/SETUP.md` — add "Updating an Existing Node" section pointing to UPDATE.md

### 21. `setup.sh` — Forward to `update.sh` on Already-Installed Nodes

**Problem:** Running `setup.sh` on a node that was already installed would re-initialize databases, credentials, and node identity — potentially destroying data.

**Fix:** `setup.sh` now detects existing installs (`/etc/aitbc/node.env` + `/opt/aitbc/venv` both present) and forwards to `update.sh` instead of re-running the full first-time install. Added `--force` flag to bypass the forward for repair scenarios.

**Files changed:**
- `scripts/deployment/setup.sh` — add install detection + `--force` flag + forward logic
- `docs/getting-started/SETUP.md` — document `--force` and forwarding behavior

### 22. Nginx Examples: Role-Specific Configs

**Problem:** The single monolithic `nginx-aitbc.conf.example` mixed hub and shop services, requiring operators to manually comment out sections per role. The host reverse proxy had the same problem. A redundant `nginx-follower.conf` existed (follower is a blockchain mode, not a market role).

**Fix:** Split into 6 role-specific files — 3 container configs + 3 host proxy configs, with clean 1:1 pairing:

| Role | Container config | Host proxy config |
|---|---|---|
| Hub | `nginx-hub.conf.example` | `nginx-hub-proxy.conf.example` |
| Shop | `nginx-shop.conf.example` | `nginx-shop-proxy.conf.example` |
| Customer | `nginx-customer.conf.example` | `nginx-customer-proxy.conf.example` |

Each config only includes the locations its role needs — no commenting out required. Added architecture notes explaining that nginx is for external traffic only (internal service-to-service communication uses localhost directly, e.g. `gpu_worker.py` → `localhost:8203`).

`setup.sh` and `update.sh` now print role-specific nginx config hints at the end of a successful run, pointing the sysadmin to the right container config + host proxy config pair.

**Files changed:**
- `examples/nginx/nginx-hub.conf.example` — new (split from monolithic config)
